  1. This problem focuses on the collinearity problem.
  1. Perform the following commands in R: The last line corresponds to creating a linear model in which y is a function of x1 and x2. Write out the form of the linear model. What are the regression coefficients?
set.seed(1)
x1=runif(100)
x2=0.5*x1+rnorm(100)/10
y <- 2+2*x1+0.3*x2+rnorm(100)
head(y, n = 5)
## [1] 3.0329739 2.7631458 2.9237999 2.9894037 0.9891466

The linear model is y = 2 + 2 * x1 + 0.3 * x2 + E

  1. What is the correlation between x1 and x2? Create a scatterplot displaying the relationship between the variables.
cor(x1, x2)
## [1] 0.8351212
plot(x1, x2)

  1. Using this data, fit a least squares regression to predict y using x1 and x2. Describe the results obtained. What are βˆ0, βˆ1, and βˆ2? How do these relate to the true β0, β1, and β2? Can you reject the null hypothesis H0 : β1 = 0? How about the null hypothesis H0 : β2 = 0?
model1 <- lm(y ~ x1 + x2)

summary(model1)

R2 closer to 1 is the best fit regression line. The R2 is only .2088 which is very low and may not be good model.

βˆ0 = 2.1305 βˆ1 = 1.4396 βˆ2 = 1.0097

x1 has a low p value of 0.0487. So we can reject the null hypothesis H0 : β1 = 0

x2 has a high p value of 0.3754. So we will fail to reject the null hypothesis H0 : β2 = 0.

  1. Do the results obtained in (c)–(e) contradict each other? Explain your answer.

No. As the predictors x1 and x2 are highly correlated, it has collinearity so is diffcult to predict how each predictor is associated with the reponse separately. Collinearity causes the standard errors to grow in model1 for x2 is 1.1337, and the test statistics (β/SE ) declines and we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

the Q-Q plot is approxmately normal for x1 and x2 separately but not when both are included in the model.

In the Residual vs. ftted graph for x1 and x2, we do see some overlapping of data points. This is apparently due to collinearity.

In the Residual vs. fitted graph for x2, a single predictor towards the rightmost is a high leverage point with high value of predictor.

In the model with x1, a single prdictor is an outlier, that is having an unusual response value.
